6 Initial Colors & Styling

6.1 Challenge 1: 3 Different Versions

First, make all the columns outlined in “white”.

ggplot(hot_dogs, aes(x = year, y = num_eaten)) + 
  geom_col(colour = "white") + 
  labs(x = "Year", y = "Hot Dogs and Buns Consumed") +
  ggtitle("Nathan's Hot Dog Eating Contest Results, 1981-2017")

Second, make all the columns outlined in “white” and filled in “lightblue” (I changed “navyblue” to “lightblue” because I prefer the latter.)

ggplot(hot_dogs, aes(x = year, y = num_eaten)) + 
  geom_col(colour = "white", fill = "lightblue") + 
  labs(x = "Year", y = "Hot Dogs and Buns Consumed") +
  ggtitle("Nathan's Hot Dog Eating Contest Results, 1981-2017")

Third, make all the columns outlined in “white” and filled in according to whether or not post_ifoce is TRUE or FALSE (use default colors for now).

ggplot(hot_dogs, aes(x = year, y = num_eaten)) + 
  geom_col(aes(fill = post_ifoce), colour = "white") + 
  labs(x = "Year", y = "Hot Dogs and Buns Consumed") +
  ggtitle("Nathan's Hot Dog Eating Contest Results, 1981-2017")

6.2 Challenge 2: Adjusting the Legend

Delete the legend title and make the legend text either “Post-IFOCE” or “Pre-IFOCE”.

ggplot(hot_dogs, aes(x = year, y = num_eaten)) + 
  geom_col(aes(fill = post_ifoce), colour = "white") + 
  labs(x = "Year", y = "Hot Dogs and Buns Consumed") +
  ggtitle("Nathan's Hot Dog Eating Contest Results, 1981-2017") +
  scale_fill_discrete(name = "",
                      labels=c("Pre-IFOCE", "Post-IFOCE"))

7 Change the Dataset

IFOCE affiliation analysis

7.1 Challenge 3: Adding Columns, Filtering

hdm_affil <- read_csv(here::here("data", "hot_dog_contest_with_affiliation.csv"), 
    col_types = cols(
      affiliated = col_factor(levels = NULL), 
      gender = col_factor(levels = NULL)
      )) %>% 
  mutate(post_ifoce = year >= 1997) %>% 
  filter(year >= 1981 & gender == "male")

7.3 Updated Plot

Now plot this new data, and fill the columns according to our new affiliated column.

ggplot(hdm_affil, aes(x = year, y = num_eaten)) + 
  geom_col(aes(fill = affiliated)) + 
  labs(x = "Year", y = "Hot Dogs and Buns Consumed") +
  ggtitle("Nathan's Hot Dog Eating Contest Results, 1981-2017")

7.4 Challenge 5: Adjusting the Colors

Update the colors using hex colors: c(‘#E9602B’,‘#2277A0’,‘#CCB683’), change the legend title to “IFOCE-affiliation”, and save this plot object as “affil_plot”.

affil_plot <- ggplot(hdm_affil, aes(x = year, y = num_eaten)) + 
  geom_col(aes(fill = affiliated)) + 
  labs(x = "Year", y = "Hot Dogs and Buns Consumed") +
  ggtitle("Nathan's Hot Dog Eating Contest Results, 1981-2017") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c('#E9602B','#2277A0','#CCB683'),
                    name = "IFOCE-affiliation")
affil_plot

8 Sweating the Details

8.1 Initial plot

affil_plot

8.2 Challenge 6: Custom Axes

Tighten scales and coordinates up.

affil_plot <- affil_plot + 
  scale_y_continuous(expand = c(0, 0),
                     breaks = seq(0, 70, 10)) +
  scale_x_continuous(expand = c(0, 0))
affil_plot

loosen things up a bit by setting the x-axis range to 1980-2018 and the y-axis range to 0-80.

affil_plot <- affil_plot + 
  coord_cartesian(xlim = c(1980, 2018), ylim = c(0, 80)) 
affil_plot

9.1 Initial Plot

9.2 Making a Custom Theme

hot_diggity<- theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
  theme(axis.text = element_text(size =8)) +
  theme(panel.background = element_blank())+
  theme(axis.line.x = element_line(color = "gray80",size=0.5)) +
  theme(axis.ticks = element_line(color = "gray80",size = 0.5)) +
  theme(text=element_text(family = "Georgia"))
affil_plot + hot_diggity

9.3 Applying Library Themes

affil_plot + theme_wsj(base_family = "Georgia",base_size = 6)

9.4 Custom Tick Marks & Labels

Mess with the x-axis ticks and labels.

years_to_label <- seq(from = 1981, to = 2017, by=6)
hd_years <- hdm_affil %>%
  distinct(year) %>%
  mutate(year_lab = ifelse(year %in% years_to_label,year,""))

10 Finalizing Our Masterpiece!

nathan_plot <- affil_plot +
  theme_wsj(base_size = 6, base_family = "Georgia") +
  scale_x_continuous(expand =c(0,0),
                     breaks = hd_years$year,
                     labels = hd_years$year_lab)

replace the existing scale.

10.2 Adding an Additional Data Layer

First, load data and filter it to obtain data from female contestants.

hdm_females <- read_csv(here::here("data", "hot_dog_contest_with_affiliation.csv"), 
    col_types = cols(
      affiliated = col_factor(levels = NULL), 
      gender = col_factor(levels = NULL)
      )) %>% 
  mutate(post_ifoce = year >= 1997) %>% 
  filter(year >= 1981 & gender == "female") 
glimpse(hdm_females)

nathan_w_females <- nathan_ann +
  # add in the female data, and manually set a fill color
  geom_col(data = hdm_females, 
           width = 0.75, 
           fill = "lightblue") 
nathan_w_females

Add a final caption.

caption <- paste(strwrap("! From 2011 on, separate Men's and Women's prizes have been awarded. All female champions to date have been MLE/IFOCE-affiliated.", 70), collapse="\n")

nathan_w_females +
  annotate('text', x = 2018.5, y = 39, label="!", family = "Georgia", size = 6) +
  labs(caption = caption) +
